1
00:00:04,421 --> 00:00:05,255
[Mr. Burns grunts]

2
00:00:05,256 --> 00:00:07,298
I'm just gonna attach this lapel mic, sir.

3
00:00:08,341 --> 00:00:09,634
[Mr. Burns groans]

4
00:00:10,719 --> 00:00:13,512
{\an8}So you want me to talk about
Persephone Odair. That's easy.

5
00:00:13,513 --> 00:00:16,682
{\an8}She was a brilliant entrepreneur
who wanted to save the world.

6
00:00:16,683 --> 00:00:19,310
{\an8}How I wish that was her only shortcoming.

7
00:00:20,729 --> 00:00:24,398
{\an8}My company, LifeBoat,
can take an ocean of salt water

8
00:00:24,399 --> 00:00:28,444
{\an8}and transform it into clean drinking water
cheaply and efficiently,

9
00:00:28,445 --> 00:00:31,739
{\an8}with a machine only the size
of a can of oats.

10
00:00:31,740 --> 00:00:33,407
{\an8}[audience gasps] Oats!

11
00:00:33,408 --> 00:00:36,452
{\an8}Now, the doubters
call this goal impossible.

12
00:00:36,453 --> 00:00:39,747
{\an8}But I prefer to say, "I'm possible."

13
00:00:39,748 --> 00:00:41,331
{\an8}[audience applauds]

14
00:00:41,332 --> 00:00:43,126
{\an8}[documentary music playing]

15
00:00:46,588 --> 00:00:49,006
{\an8}[narrator] <i>This story's about
a little girl who had a dream.</i>

16
00:00:49,007 --> 00:00:52,009
{\an8}<i>But it begins with another little girl
who allowed us to use the footage</i>

17
00:00:52,010 --> 00:00:55,721
{\an8}<i>from when she interviewed the first little
girl who was no longer a little girl.</i>

18
00:00:55,722 --> 00:01:01,477
<i>I'm so excited to be interviewing
Persephone Odair, CEO of LifeBoat.</i>

19
00:01:01,478 --> 00:01:05,856
{\an8}<i>So, Persephone, you were the most
be-badged Girl Scout of all time,</i>

20
00:01:05,857 --> 00:01:10,277
{\an8}<i>and then followed in the footsteps of Bill
Gates by dropping out of Harvard early.</i>

21
00:01:10,278 --> 00:01:11,945
{\an8}<i>The earliest ever.</i>

22
00:01:11,946 --> 00:01:14,866
<i>Our car didn't even slow down
on freshman move-in day.</i>

23
00:01:17,368 --> 00:01:19,078
<i>So inspirational.</i>

24
00:01:19,079 --> 00:01:23,791
<i>What was the aha moment that gave you
the idea to start LifeBoat?</i>

25
00:01:23,792 --> 00:01:25,000
{\an8}<i>Great question.</i>

26
00:01:25,001 --> 00:01:28,045
{\an8}<i>And, Lisa, great questions are
the jackhammers</i>

27
00:01:28,046 --> 00:01:30,714
{\an8}<i>which demo the walls
built by disruptophobes</i>

28
00:01:30,715 --> 00:01:33,801
{\an8}<i>to create the open floor plan
of innovation.</i>

29
00:01:33,802 --> 00:01:36,470
<i>I've always thought that about questions.</i>

30
00:01:36,471 --> 00:01:39,264
[Persephone] <i>Lisa,
my grandfather was a World War II sailor</i>

31
00:01:39,265 --> 00:01:40,349
<i>whose ship was torpedoed.</i>

32
00:01:40,350 --> 00:01:42,935
<i>He was stranded on a lifeboat, Lisa.</i>

33
00:01:42,936 --> 00:01:46,647
<i>Surrounded by water,
but not a drop to drink.</i>

34
00:01:46,648 --> 00:01:48,524
<i>Don't tell me he died.</i>

35
00:01:48,525 --> 00:01:54,571
{\an8}<i>Worse. He gave up and then he died of
quitting and super-duper dehydration.</i>

36
00:01:54,572 --> 00:01:56,365
{\an8}<i>But I will never give up</i>

37
00:01:56,366 --> 00:01:59,827
{\an8}<i>until I've raised enough capital
to make LifeBoat a reality.</i>

38
00:01:59,828 --> 00:02:02,121
{\an8}<i>So if you know any billionaires...</i>
[chuckles]

39
00:02:02,122 --> 00:02:06,041
{\an8}<i>Well, the only one in our town
is Mr. Burns, and he's awful.</i>

40
00:02:06,042 --> 00:02:08,418
{\an8}<i>Once, he clear-cut a forest</i>

41
00:02:08,419 --> 00:02:11,004
{\an8}<i>because he thought
a squirrel was looking at him funny.</i>

42
00:02:11,005 --> 00:02:13,924
[dramatic music plays]

43
00:02:13,925 --> 00:02:15,968
{\an8}<i>Montgomery Burns. Mmm.</i>

44
00:02:15,969 --> 00:02:17,929
{\an8}<i>Interesting idea, Lisa.</i>

45
00:02:18,471 --> 00:02:20,347
{\an8}<i>No, I didn't say it to be an idea.</i>

46
00:02:20,348 --> 00:02:21,640
{\an8}<i>He's terrible.</i>

47
00:02:21,641 --> 00:02:24,434
{\an8}<i>Whatever you do, don't go to him.</i>

48
00:02:24,435 --> 00:02:27,604
{\an8}[narrator] <i>But the woman who once
tried to clone Sheryl Sandberg</i>

49
00:02:27,605 --> 00:02:30,316
{\an8}<i>for a school project
would not be deterred.</i>

50
00:02:33,736 --> 00:02:37,990
Welcome to Orlando. Quick heads-up,
we may have to cut this panel short

51
00:02:37,991 --> 00:02:41,577
due to our third once-in-a-million-year
hurricane this season.

52
00:02:41,578 --> 00:02:44,246
- [wind whistling]
- Put this on my reel!

53
00:02:44,247 --> 00:02:45,622
Terrible luck.

54
00:02:45,623 --> 00:02:47,207
No fault of anyone's.

55
00:02:47,208 --> 00:02:50,502
Mr. Burns, climate change
has left the Earth in peril.

56
00:02:50,503 --> 00:02:55,007
{\an8}Who sent you? John Muir?
Friedrich Engels? Mike Doonesbury?

57
00:02:55,008 --> 00:02:59,554
I'm getting word that this hurricane is
meeting up with the Everglades super fire.

58
00:03:00,763 --> 00:03:03,849
Montgomery, I'm the founder
of a desalination company.

59
00:03:03,850 --> 00:03:09,021
Our world is running out of water,
and we need a hero to rescue us,

60
00:03:09,022 --> 00:03:12,191
and I believe that
that hero is your money.

61
00:03:12,192 --> 00:03:13,359
[wind whistling]

62
00:03:14,777 --> 00:03:17,112
{\an8}We sell chemicals
that could put out that fire.

63
00:03:17,113 --> 00:03:20,157
Granted, those chemicals
turn alligators into Godzillas.

64
00:03:20,158 --> 00:03:23,202
But we're working on a bomb
that can fix that.

65
00:03:23,203 --> 00:03:25,913
{\an8}Sorry, miss. Desalination is a snooze.

66
00:03:25,914 --> 00:03:28,458
But I do want in on the Godzilla bomb.

67
00:03:29,792 --> 00:03:32,669
[narrator] <i>Persephone was not shy about
hounding Mr. Burns.</i>

68
00:03:32,670 --> 00:03:35,506
<i>And he wasn't shy about hounding her.</i>

69
00:03:36,758 --> 00:03:38,717
Some fish just swim with the tide.

70
00:03:38,718 --> 00:03:42,554
I'm the kind of relentless fish
that falls down ten times

71
00:03:42,555 --> 00:03:46,935
before it runs up the mountain
on ocean shoes.

72
00:03:53,107 --> 00:03:54,525
[airplane approaching]

73
00:04:00,740 --> 00:04:03,325
[groans] Fine. You've got five minutes.

74
00:04:03,326 --> 00:04:05,452
Who are these goateed wastrels?

75
00:04:05,453 --> 00:04:06,578
A documentary crew.

76
00:04:06,579 --> 00:04:10,582
Only the most paradigm-shifting
start-up CEOs have them.

77
00:04:10,583 --> 00:04:14,753
Mr. Burns, I see your life
as a beautiful business opera

78
00:04:14,754 --> 00:04:18,006
and investing in LifeBoat
as the climactic aria

79
00:04:18,007 --> 00:04:23,095
{\an8}that will put you in the same pantheon
as Getty, Vanderbilt, the Spanx lady.

80
00:04:23,096 --> 00:04:26,848
Desalination is an expensive
and inefficient industry

81
00:04:26,849 --> 00:04:28,517
begging to be disrupted.

82
00:04:28,518 --> 00:04:30,686
Success is a decision.

83
00:04:30,687 --> 00:04:33,480
Dare to choose it, sir. Dare to.

84
00:04:33,481 --> 00:04:34,564
Of course.

85
00:04:34,565 --> 00:04:36,775
Like how I chose to be born rich.

86
00:04:36,776 --> 00:04:39,820
Together we can disrupt big salt water.

87
00:04:39,821 --> 00:04:41,822
You mean the ocean?

88
00:04:41,823 --> 00:04:42,906
Exactly.

89
00:04:42,907 --> 00:04:45,410
- Or should I say, excellent.
- Excellent.

90
00:04:46,202 --> 00:04:49,579
Not only am I pledging much of
my personal wealth to LifeBoat,

91
00:04:49,580 --> 00:04:53,709
but I'm giving the company Cooling Tower A
to use as its headquarters.

92
00:04:53,710 --> 00:04:56,503
{\an8}Cooling Tower A
was Mr. Burns's favorite tower.

93
00:04:56,504 --> 00:04:59,257
{\an8}He always said it held
so many precious memories.

94
00:05:01,718 --> 00:05:05,721
In addition, all workers in Sector 7-G
are immediately fired...

95
00:05:05,722 --> 00:05:06,847
Hey, that's me!

96
00:05:06,848 --> 00:05:08,140
Screw you, pig!

97
00:05:08,141 --> 00:05:11,518
And are rehired
at higher tech industry salaries.

98
00:05:11,519 --> 00:05:12,894
Bless you, pig!

99
00:05:12,895 --> 00:05:16,106
[narrator] <i>Burns brought his wealthiest
friends into Persephone's fold.</i>

100
00:05:16,107 --> 00:05:20,319
When I invest, I look at
the business's key fundamental:

101
00:05:20,320 --> 00:05:24,574
Am I under the delusion
that I have a shot with the CEO?

102
00:05:25,616 --> 00:05:26,617
[chuckling]

103
00:05:27,744 --> 00:05:31,496
[narrator] <i>Burns and Persephone were soon
running the new company side by side,</i>

104
00:05:31,497 --> 00:05:35,000
<i>overseeing a start-up culture
where everyone had a creative title.</i>

105
00:05:35,001 --> 00:05:38,670
Persephone Odair, Founder
and Status Quo Demolitionist.

106
00:05:38,671 --> 00:05:41,423
Montgomery Burns, Chief Change Alchemist.

107
00:05:41,424 --> 00:05:43,842
Waylon Smithers, Purposefulness Warlock.

108
00:05:43,843 --> 00:05:46,178
Carl Carlson, Brain Dump Magician.

109
00:05:46,179 --> 00:05:48,513
Lenny Leonard, Storytelling Ninja.

110
00:05:48,514 --> 00:05:50,891
Homer Simpson, "Competeticy" Rock Star.

111
00:05:50,892 --> 00:05:52,309
[producer] Competency.

112
00:05:52,310 --> 00:05:53,685
Say it again.

113
00:05:53,686 --> 00:05:57,022
{\an8}If anyone can transform Burns,
it's a visionary like Persephone.

114
00:05:57,023 --> 00:06:00,400
{\an8}Like, if you work at LifeBoat, you have to
use these metal drinking straws.

115
00:06:00,401 --> 00:06:03,028
It's so easy to clean after every use.

116
00:06:03,029 --> 00:06:04,237
[grunting]

117
00:06:04,238 --> 00:06:05,572
I'm just... [groans]

118
00:06:05,573 --> 00:06:07,324
Why does it have to bend?

119
00:06:07,325 --> 00:06:09,117
Come... [grunts]

120
00:06:09,118 --> 00:06:11,703
{\an8}<i>♪ This is my fight song ♪</i>

121
00:06:11,704 --> 00:06:14,623
<i>♪ Take back my life song ♪</i>

122
00:06:14,624 --> 00:06:18,126
<i>♪ Prove I'm all right song ♪</i>

123
00:06:18,127 --> 00:06:19,420
[Mr. Burns grunting]

124
00:06:23,424 --> 00:06:25,342
My fellow LifeBoaters!

125
00:06:25,343 --> 00:06:28,970
I'm so excited to have you
on this journey with me.

126
00:06:28,971 --> 00:06:33,225
Imagine a world
with an endless supply of drinkable water.

127
00:06:33,226 --> 00:06:40,274
A world where every hotel towel can be
used once and then dropped on the floor.

128
00:06:40,900 --> 00:06:42,275
Oh, there were a lot of changes.

129
00:06:42,276 --> 00:06:46,071
Unlike when this was a nuclear plant,
security's super tight now,

130
00:06:46,072 --> 00:06:48,657
and we have to sign stringent NDAs.

131
00:06:48,658 --> 00:06:51,034
And I am bad at keeping secrets.

132
00:06:51,035 --> 00:06:54,955
Like how I'm not supposed to talk about
Lenny's crush on his Italian tutor.

133
00:06:54,956 --> 00:06:57,499
Homer, <i>ti ammazzo</i>. [speaking Italian]

134
00:06:57,500 --> 00:07:00,502
{\an8}[narrator] <i>LifeBoat was soaring,
but no one could have predicted</i>

135
00:07:00,503 --> 00:07:03,213
{\an8}<i>what shocking turn was in store
for the company.</i>

136
00:07:03,214 --> 00:07:05,298
Um. Is this one of those documentaries

137
00:07:05,299 --> 00:07:07,300
where I'm not supposed
to look at the camera?

138
00:07:07,301 --> 00:07:10,262
Or is it like <i>The Office</i>,
where I always look at it

139
00:07:10,263 --> 00:07:13,349
and do a big take so the audience
knows when to laugh?

140
00:07:16,227 --> 00:07:19,479
"...in richness and wealth,
for richer and richer,"

141
00:07:19,480 --> 00:07:23,276
I now pronounce you husband and wife.

142
00:07:28,573 --> 00:07:29,949
[documentary music playing]

143
00:07:31,742 --> 00:07:33,118
I'm still pinching myself.

144
00:07:33,119 --> 00:07:38,206
I'm married to Montgomery Burns,
nuclear industry legend.

145
00:07:38,207 --> 00:07:41,042
Chief s'more toaster
at the Bohemian Grove.

146
00:07:41,043 --> 00:07:43,086
The first man with no blood type.

147
00:07:43,087 --> 00:07:46,548
What a joy to wake up in the morning,
turn my head on the pillow,

148
00:07:46,549 --> 00:07:50,844
<i>and see her bedroom door through
the glass of my hyperbaric chamber.</i>

149
00:07:50,845 --> 00:07:54,599
[narrator] <i>Soon, Persephone and Burns were
the new It power couple.</i>

150
00:07:59,687 --> 00:08:04,524
<i>And the press couldn't get enough of
this May-last-minute-of-December romance.</i>

151
00:08:04,525 --> 00:08:08,361
It's so refreshing to see a young person
with the world at her feet,

152
00:08:08,362 --> 00:08:11,782
who also sees the glory that is
Montgomery Burns.

153
00:08:22,084 --> 00:08:23,168
[swallows, grunts]

154
00:08:23,169 --> 00:08:26,087
[narrator] <i>Now it was up to Persephone
to create a working prototype</i>

155
00:08:26,088 --> 00:08:28,591
<i>of her amazing desalination technology.</i>

156
00:08:29,175 --> 00:08:31,968
{\an8}The water in front of you comes from
the functional prototype

157
00:08:31,969 --> 00:08:34,596
of the LifeBoat desalination machine.

158
00:08:34,597 --> 00:08:39,227
So, everyone, please raise a glass
to milestone this history-defining moment.

159
00:08:40,269 --> 00:08:41,978
- [murmuring]
- What's going on?

160
00:08:41,979 --> 00:08:44,439
- Hey...
- Oh, no, you can't drink it now. No.

161
00:08:44,440 --> 00:08:48,068
Our competitors could steal
the proprietary aquatech in your urine.

162
00:08:48,069 --> 00:08:50,487
[chuckling, chattering]

163
00:08:50,488 --> 00:08:53,532
And just in case any of
our patented evaporated mist

164
00:08:53,533 --> 00:08:54,866
made it into your bladders,

165
00:08:54,867 --> 00:08:57,827
we've arranged
to have you all catheterized.

166
00:08:57,828 --> 00:08:59,788
- [chattering]
- Ooh! Yeah!

167
00:08:59,789 --> 00:09:01,915
[catheter whirring]

168
00:09:01,916 --> 00:09:04,960
{\an8}So LifeBoat was just following
the tech industry playbook.

169
00:09:04,961 --> 00:09:10,006
{\an8}Fake it till you make it.
Or as I call it "lie-PO" until you IPO.

170
00:09:10,007 --> 00:09:13,260
{\an8}But the employees
were already dreaming of cashing out.

171
00:09:13,261 --> 00:09:15,387
Tech salaries are the greatest.

172
00:09:15,388 --> 00:09:19,349
This week I gave Marge 200 stock options
to go grocery shopping.

173
00:09:19,350 --> 00:09:20,600
It didn't work at all.

174
00:09:20,601 --> 00:09:23,520
I had to put all the food
back on the shelves.

175
00:09:23,521 --> 00:09:26,606
[narrator] <i>Meanwhile, the newly-minted
tech workers were adapting to</i>

176
00:09:26,607 --> 00:09:28,775
<i>a much different corporate culture.</i>

177
00:09:28,776 --> 00:09:31,361
At the new company,
people were so secretive,

178
00:09:31,362 --> 00:09:35,616
they actually moved the Post-it notes
with their passwords off their monitor.

179
00:09:38,953 --> 00:09:41,913
[Homer]
<i>Workers were getting fired every day.</i>

180
00:09:41,914 --> 00:09:44,709
That tattoo is the intellectual property
of the company.

181
00:09:47,378 --> 00:09:50,589
The whole company got so paranoid.

182
00:09:50,590 --> 00:09:55,719
Because of those NDAs he signed, Homer
couldn't even tell me how his day was.

183
00:09:55,720 --> 00:09:57,971
I can neither confirm
nor deny I had a day.

184
00:09:57,972 --> 00:10:01,891
Well, it was strange they wouldn't
let me look inside the machine,

185
00:10:01,892 --> 00:10:07,063
since my title was Chief Engineer
of Inside the Machine. [coughs]

186
00:10:07,064 --> 00:10:08,690
[Professor Frink]
<i>Whenever a reporter came by,</i>

187
00:10:08,691 --> 00:10:12,153
<i>it seemed like they were trying to
cover something up.</i>

188
00:10:12,820 --> 00:10:16,781
Well, still better than
working for Zuckerberg.

189
00:10:16,782 --> 00:10:20,201
They were hiding something,
and it was really freaking me out.

190
00:10:20,202 --> 00:10:21,786
So I emailed Persephone.

191
00:10:21,787 --> 00:10:24,040
And the next day, Carl was gone.

192
00:10:32,298 --> 00:10:34,716
[narrator] <i>Despite the red flags flying
from this lifeboat,</i>

193
00:10:34,717 --> 00:10:36,468
<i>there continued to be believers.</i>

194
00:10:36,469 --> 00:10:39,179
Persephone dominates my vision board.

195
00:10:39,180 --> 00:10:44,267
Sure, she married Mr. Burns,
but as CEO, a woman had all the power.

196
00:10:44,268 --> 00:10:47,228
That's what made
the Internet trolls so mad.

197
00:10:47,229 --> 00:10:49,356
[narrator]
<i>All the online negativity stirred up</i>

198
00:10:49,357 --> 00:10:53,151
<i>the finger-tented anger
of a different kind of troll.</i>

199
00:10:53,152 --> 00:10:54,444
Hmm.

200
00:10:54,445 --> 00:10:56,863
<i>♪ This is my fight song ♪</i>

201
00:10:56,864 --> 00:10:59,949
<i>♪ Take back my life song ♪</i>

202
00:10:59,950 --> 00:11:01,701
I wanted to give my wife...

203
00:11:01,702 --> 00:11:04,204
Wow. "Wife."
Still getting used to saying that.

204
00:11:04,205 --> 00:11:06,831
A little something special
for her birthday.

205
00:11:06,832 --> 00:11:08,416
A Twitter gift card?

206
00:11:08,417 --> 00:11:12,170
No. I bought you Twitter.
The whole company.

207
00:11:12,171 --> 00:11:13,296
It was a bargain.

208
00:11:13,297 --> 00:11:14,714
The previous owner had to sell it

209
00:11:14,715 --> 00:11:19,302
after his self-driving Mars rocket crashed
into the International Space Station.

210
00:11:19,303 --> 00:11:20,887
[Persephone moans]

211
00:11:20,888 --> 00:11:24,307
Mr. Burns, you deleted all negative tweets
about Persephone.

212
00:11:24,308 --> 00:11:26,559
Is that evidence
that you're in a kind of cult

213
00:11:26,560 --> 00:11:28,895
and won't hear any criticism
of your leader?

214
00:11:28,896 --> 00:11:33,191
Yes, I am in a cult.
It's called a marriage. [laughs]

215
00:11:33,192 --> 00:11:36,027
My wife is the head of it,
and my job is to support her.

216
00:11:36,028 --> 00:11:38,988
Now, maybe you're the cult leader
in your marriage, Andrew,

217
00:11:38,989 --> 00:11:42,992
but, uh, I know Pilar
and I suspect she'd disagree. [laughs]

218
00:11:42,993 --> 00:11:44,744
[both laugh]

219
00:11:44,745 --> 00:11:47,330
[narrator] <i>But LifeBoat was rocked
by a fresh scandal,</i>

220
00:11:47,331 --> 00:11:51,793
{\an8}<i>when an anonymous whistleblower bravely
came forward with damning new information.</i>

221
00:11:51,794 --> 00:11:53,837
{\an8}[low-pitched, distorted]
My best friend, Carl, was abducted

222
00:11:53,838 --> 00:11:57,424
{\an8}because he was about to go public with
a story that would destroy this company.

223
00:11:57,425 --> 00:12:01,177
{\an8}People need to know the truth.
The LifeBoat machine doesn't work.

224
00:12:01,178 --> 00:12:04,140
[narrator] <i>The whistle was blown
and the damage was done.</i>

225
00:12:11,272 --> 00:12:13,898
Ma'am, ma'am.
The whistleblower claims the only person

226
00:12:13,899 --> 00:12:17,110
who has seen the inside of
your desalination machine has disappeared.

227
00:12:17,111 --> 00:12:18,611
Isn't that suspicious?

228
00:12:18,612 --> 00:12:20,196
Why do you doubt a female CEO,

229
00:12:20,197 --> 00:12:23,199
but believe the silhouette
of a man sitting in the dark?

230
00:12:23,200 --> 00:12:26,120
News flash, women have faces now.

231
00:12:26,620 --> 00:12:27,620
[narrator] <i>At this moment,</i>

232
00:12:27,621 --> 00:12:30,540
<i>allegations that
its core technology does not work</i>

233
00:12:30,541 --> 00:12:33,126
<i>are threatening LifeBoat's very survival.</i>

234
00:12:33,127 --> 00:12:37,172
<i>Is this the beginning of the end
for this once promising start-up?</i>

235
00:12:37,173 --> 00:12:40,091
[narrator 2]
<i>And the answer is, absolutely not.</i>

236
00:12:40,092 --> 00:12:44,471
<i>LifeBoat will save humanity and become
the world's most profitable company.</i>

237
00:12:44,472 --> 00:12:49,517
<i>Join us next time for</i> LifeBoat Afloat:
Persephone's Total Vindication.

238
00:12:49,518 --> 00:12:53,272
{\an8}[Mr. Burns] <i>This documentary series
is now a BurnsCo production.</i>

239
00:12:56,525 --> 00:12:59,986
Montgomery Burns wasn't happy with
the documentary about his wife's start-up,

240
00:12:59,987 --> 00:13:02,113
so he bought the company that made it.

241
00:13:02,114 --> 00:13:04,449
But that didn't stop others
from telling the story,

242
00:13:04,450 --> 00:13:08,704
because the business
of business documentaries is big business.

243
00:13:10,790 --> 00:13:13,792
We've unearthed even more
never-before-seen footage of the Beatles.

244
00:13:13,793 --> 00:13:16,961
Including six hours
of them discussing drinking water.

245
00:13:16,962 --> 00:13:20,381
The thing about water,
you can't make tea without it.

246
00:13:20,382 --> 00:13:22,550
What if you made tea out of coffee?

247
00:13:22,551 --> 00:13:24,636
What if you made coffee out of tea?

248
00:13:24,637 --> 00:13:27,139
Uh, fellas,
maybe we should play some music.

249
00:13:28,182 --> 00:13:32,102
Why do they call it H2O?
I bet no reason at all.

250
00:13:32,603 --> 00:13:34,062
[glass shatters]

251
00:13:34,063 --> 00:13:35,396
[narrator] <i>Just weeks ago,</i>

252
00:13:35,397 --> 00:13:38,609
<i>LifeBoat stopped payment
on their stadium-naming rights.</i>

253
00:13:45,658 --> 00:13:47,867
Despite the glut
of LifeBoat documentaries,

254
00:13:47,868 --> 00:13:50,829
the definitive version was made
by a storyteller so compelling,

255
00:13:50,830 --> 00:13:54,415
he made 12 hours
on the national parks feel like 11.

256
00:13:54,416 --> 00:13:56,043
[ambient music playing]

257
00:14:10,891 --> 00:14:13,017
[Peter Coyote]
<i>The mysterious whistleblower alleged that</i>

258
00:14:13,018 --> 00:14:16,396
<i>Persephone's desalination
machine was fraudulent.</i>

259
00:14:16,397 --> 00:14:19,190
{\an8}[low-pitched, distorted]
The LifeBoat machine doesn't work.

260
00:14:19,191 --> 00:14:20,650
{\an8}[Peter Coyote] <i>Unfortunately for him,</i>

261
00:14:20,651 --> 00:14:23,611
{\an8}<i>Mr. Burns's legal team
had acquired the raw footage</i>

262
00:14:23,612 --> 00:14:26,823
{\an8}<i>of the whistleblower's damning interview.</i>

263
00:14:26,824 --> 00:14:29,033
{\an8}[low-pitched, distorted]
The machine doesn't work.

264
00:14:29,034 --> 00:14:33,162
{\an8}Hey! I ordered this sub toasted.
This is only lightly toasted.

265
00:14:33,163 --> 00:14:36,499
{\an8}[normal] Is this how you treat
a whistleblower? Uh-oh.

266
00:14:36,500 --> 00:14:39,377
[Peter Coyote] <i>Mr. Burns and Persephone
now knew the identity</i>

267
00:14:39,378 --> 00:14:41,421
<i>of the man who betrayed them.</i>

268
00:14:41,422 --> 00:14:44,507
<i>And the hiring of lawyers
to destroy Homer Simpson</i>

269
00:14:44,508 --> 00:14:47,468
<i>proved to be quite the aphrodisiac.</i>

270
00:14:47,469 --> 00:14:48,720
[no audible dialogue]

271
00:14:48,721 --> 00:14:51,222
[Mr. Burns, Persephone moaning]

272
00:14:51,223 --> 00:14:54,350
[Peter Coyote] <i>LifeBoat lawyers were
relentless in trying to subpoena Homer...</i>

273
00:14:54,351 --> 00:14:57,563
- [Homer screams]
- <i>...and sue him for breaking his NDA.</i>

274
00:15:03,444 --> 00:15:07,113
[Lisa] <i>My dad got an anonymous message
saying there was something he had to see,</i>

275
00:15:07,114 --> 00:15:08,615
<i>so I went with him.</i>

276
00:15:08,616 --> 00:15:13,369
What I saw changed the one thing
I thought could never be changed,

277
00:15:13,370 --> 00:15:14,538
my mind.

278
00:15:21,670 --> 00:15:26,383
[gasps] Carl, you sent the message.
You've been working in the lab all along?

279
00:15:29,345 --> 00:15:33,097
If I didn't do their dirty work,
they'd tell the world my dark secret.

280
00:15:33,098 --> 00:15:37,018
I've been to 700 Jimmy Buffett concerts.
I'm a Parrot Head.

281
00:15:37,019 --> 00:15:39,687
"Cheeseburger in Paradise"!

282
00:15:39,688 --> 00:15:41,606
[Lisa] So, what are they making you do?

283
00:15:41,607 --> 00:15:46,027
I'm putting something in the LifeBoat
machines called Jab-a-tose.

284
00:15:46,028 --> 00:15:48,029
Well, if I may Frink-splain,

285
00:15:48,030 --> 00:15:53,618
{\an8}in 1970, a very popular diet soda
called Jab was discontinued

286
00:15:53,619 --> 00:15:57,831
{\an8}<i>because of the overpowering sweetness
of its artificial flavor.</i>

287
00:15:58,874 --> 00:16:03,252
{\an8}<i>LifeBoat bought up thousands
of cases of unsold Jab sodas,</i>

288
00:16:03,253 --> 00:16:09,217
{\an8}because Jab-a-tose was so strong, it could
completely mask the taste of salt.

289
00:16:09,218 --> 00:16:10,343
Oh, my God.

290
00:16:10,344 --> 00:16:13,137
This machine doesn't take out the salt.

291
00:16:13,138 --> 00:16:15,515
It masks it with sweetness.

292
00:16:15,516 --> 00:16:16,976
That's the Jab-a-tose.

293
00:16:17,476 --> 00:16:21,688
<i>Ocean water enters the machine
and when it comes out, it tastes normal,</i>

294
00:16:21,689 --> 00:16:25,733
<i>but still has more salt
than all the glasses in Margaritaville.</i>

295
00:16:25,734 --> 00:16:26,859
Oh, my God.

296
00:16:26,860 --> 00:16:30,698
LifeBoat is built on a lie,
and Persephone is a fraud!

297
00:16:31,198 --> 00:16:34,242
But her merch is... [sniffles] ...solid.

298
00:16:34,243 --> 00:16:38,162
[Peter Coyote] <i>Action was needed,
and island time was running out.</i>

299
00:16:38,163 --> 00:16:39,998
<i>The fateful demo day had arrived</i>

300
00:16:39,999 --> 00:16:44,502
<i>for LifeBoat to finally prove its concept
at Springfield Elementary.</i>

301
00:16:44,503 --> 00:16:48,464
<i>The school's drinking water
had been replaced with LifeBoat liquid:</i>

302
00:16:48,465 --> 00:16:50,925
<i>Jab-a-tose-infused salt water.</i>

303
00:16:50,926 --> 00:16:53,594
<i>LifeBoat employees had drunk the Kool-Aid.</i>

304
00:16:53,595 --> 00:16:56,931
<i>And now it was being served up
to the children.</i>

305
00:16:56,932 --> 00:17:00,018
- [crowd cheering]
- Mr. Burns! The LifeBoat water isn't safe.

306
00:17:00,019 --> 00:17:02,353
It's just super sweetened ocean brine!

307
00:17:02,354 --> 00:17:07,233
Nonsense. My wife is a beautiful genius
who succeeds at everything she touches,

308
00:17:07,234 --> 00:17:09,736
and everything she says
makes perfect sense.

309
00:17:09,737 --> 00:17:13,031
The wheel of tomorrow is an aqua circle.

310
00:17:13,032 --> 00:17:14,824
- Let's make it rain!
- [crowd cheers]

311
00:17:14,825 --> 00:17:16,367
Buddy, buddy, buddy.

312
00:17:16,368 --> 00:17:20,788
What you're feeling towards
that lady is fresh love, not married love.

313
00:17:20,789 --> 00:17:22,081
But we are married.

314
00:17:22,082 --> 00:17:24,917
Yes, but the married love
hasn't kicked in yet.

315
00:17:24,918 --> 00:17:31,257
When it does, you'll see your spouse's
flaws in 4K HD TV you can never turn off.

316
00:17:31,258 --> 00:17:32,842
What are you driving at?

317
00:17:32,843 --> 00:17:36,096
I think you need to look
at your wife with marriage eyes.

318
00:17:36,597 --> 00:17:38,056
Water is the original crypto.

319
00:17:38,057 --> 00:17:40,725
Every drop is encoded
on the biological blockchain,

320
00:17:40,726 --> 00:17:44,103
and we are the aquanauts
of the potable future.

321
00:17:44,104 --> 00:17:46,731
- This is Wet 3.0!
- [crowd cheers]

322
00:17:46,732 --> 00:17:50,902
I don't understand a thing
she's ever said.

323
00:17:50,903 --> 00:17:52,862
Now you're married.

324
00:17:52,863 --> 00:17:55,032
{\an8}And since you're seeing things clearly...

325
00:17:56,492 --> 00:17:59,243
Oh, dear.
Those children are going to drink poison,

326
00:17:59,244 --> 00:18:02,663
and the bad news is
I am going to be liable.

327
00:18:02,664 --> 00:18:04,625
Liable!

328
00:18:07,920 --> 00:18:09,212
[children groan]

329
00:18:09,213 --> 00:18:10,296
[people scream]

330
00:18:10,297 --> 00:18:12,173
[Peter Coyote]
<i>That is what would have happened</i>

331
00:18:12,174 --> 00:18:14,802
<i>had Homer not turned the valve off.</i>

332
00:18:17,638 --> 00:18:20,181
<i>Sorry, we only put that
in there for the trailer.</i>

333
00:18:20,182 --> 00:18:23,684
<i>Do you know how hard it is to get people
to watch a documentary</i>

334
00:18:23,685 --> 00:18:25,812
<i>that's not about a small-town murder?</i>

335
00:18:25,813 --> 00:18:27,480
Please, honey, come clean.

336
00:18:27,481 --> 00:18:29,941
Your miracle invention is nothing
but claptrap.

337
00:18:29,942 --> 00:18:33,611
If you can just admit that,
maybe we have a chance.

338
00:18:33,612 --> 00:18:36,949
Babe, the underlying imaginary technology
still works.

339
00:18:37,658 --> 00:18:43,287
[Peter Coyote] <i>And in that moment, this
unlikely and super gross love affair died.</i>

340
00:18:43,288 --> 00:18:47,208
Yes, I was besotted.
Blind to her machinations.

341
00:18:47,209 --> 00:18:48,751
She cost me billions.

342
00:18:48,752 --> 00:18:51,170
It wasn't that she was evil. I love evil.

343
00:18:51,171 --> 00:18:54,049
It's that she still insists she's good.

344
00:18:55,592 --> 00:18:58,010
[Peter Coyote]
<i>LifeBoat had finally hit the reef,</i>

345
00:18:58,011 --> 00:19:01,472
<i>drowning its investors and employees
in poisoned water</i>

346
00:19:01,473 --> 00:19:03,516
<i>and counterparty risk lawsuits.</i>

347
00:19:03,517 --> 00:19:08,020
{\an8}<i>But to this day, Persephone has refused
to admit any failure.</i>

348
00:19:08,021 --> 00:19:11,357
Testing showed your desalinator
did absolutely nothing,

349
00:19:11,358 --> 00:19:12,859
your company is bankrupt,

350
00:19:12,860 --> 00:19:16,780
and in the divorce, Mr. Burns
somehow got your high school friends.

351
00:19:20,200 --> 00:19:21,534
What happens from here?

352
00:19:21,535 --> 00:19:23,161
Well, Christiane Amanpour, as you say,

353
00:19:23,162 --> 00:19:25,288
things have never looked better
for the company.

354
00:19:25,289 --> 00:19:26,581
I didn't say that.

355
00:19:26,582 --> 00:19:28,958
The reality is, you're in jail.

356
00:19:28,959 --> 00:19:30,042
[gates close]

357
00:19:30,043 --> 00:19:34,715
Christiane, have I ever told you about
my grandfather's experience on a lifeboat?

358
00:19:35,883 --> 00:19:37,216
Even that was a lie.

359
00:19:37,217 --> 00:19:40,469
Her grandfather wasn't in the war,
and he didn't die on a lifeboat.

360
00:19:40,470 --> 00:19:45,141
He's a CPA whose hobby is fixing
British spellings on Wikipedia.

361
00:19:45,142 --> 00:19:47,561
[computer keys clacking]

362
00:19:50,856 --> 00:19:54,233
[sighs] Not only did I miss out
on once-in-a-lifetime start-up riches,

363
00:19:54,234 --> 00:19:56,903
but I lost the most amazing woman
I ever met.

364
00:19:56,904 --> 00:19:59,740
I think in a few more months,
she might have even slept with me.

365
00:20:00,240 --> 00:20:03,534
It's great to meet you in person
after seeing so much footage of you

366
00:20:03,535 --> 00:20:07,080
in our documentary,
<i>The Man Who Sold Horse Meat Sandwiches</i>.

367
00:20:09,333 --> 00:20:10,499
Anything else to add?

368
00:20:10,500 --> 00:20:13,252
Just this: Don't feel sorry for me.

369
00:20:13,253 --> 00:20:15,213
Time to rebuild and reconquer.

370
00:20:15,214 --> 00:20:17,882
If I know one thing about myself,

371
00:20:17,883 --> 00:20:21,345
Montgomery Burns always bounces back.

372
00:20:26,808 --> 00:20:29,268
<i>♪ This is my fight song ♪</i>

373
00:20:29,269 --> 00:20:31,145
<i>♪ Take back my life song ♪</i>

374
00:20:31,146 --> 00:20:32,605
[Mr. Burns sobbing]

375
00:20:32,606 --> 00:20:36,943
<i>♪ Prove I'm all right song ♪</i>

376
00:20:36,944 --> 00:20:39,445
<i>♪ My power's turned on ♪</i>

377
00:20:39,446 --> 00:20:43,115
- <i>♪ Starting right now I'll be strong ♪</i>
- <i>♪ I'll be strong ♪</i>

378
00:20:43,116 --> 00:20:44,826
<i>♪ I'll play my fight song ♪</i>

379
00:20:47,079 --> 00:20:50,331
{\an8}We also have over 90 hours
of them talking about umbrellas.

380
00:20:50,332 --> 00:20:52,167
{\an8}Maybe that could be a documentary too.

381
00:20:52,751 --> 00:20:55,253
{\an8}I once brought an umbrella
into the shower.

382
00:20:55,254 --> 00:20:57,588
{\an8}- How did you get clean?
- I didn't.

383
00:20:57,589 --> 00:20:59,841
{\an8}But at least I didn't have
to take off me clothes.

384
00:21:00,926 --> 00:21:03,928
{\an8}As soon as I open my umbrella,
it stops raining.

385
00:21:03,929 --> 00:21:05,472
{\an8}You need a sunroof on it.

386
00:21:05,973 --> 00:21:08,517
{\an8}What about a giant umbrella you keep
in the trunk?

387
00:21:09,017 --> 00:21:11,520
{\an8}Sounds like you're talking
about an umbrellaphant.

388
00:21:12,020 --> 00:21:14,397
{\an8}[groans] Can we get back to work?

389
00:21:14,398 --> 00:21:16,315
{\an8}Wait, I like the sound of that.

390
00:21:16,316 --> 00:21:17,566
{\an8}"Get Back."

391
00:21:17,567 --> 00:21:21,113
{\an8}I saw an umbrellaphant at the circus.
He was working for peanuts.

392
00:21:30,122 --> 00:21:31,123
Shh!

